{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504678"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2356"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2356"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.02,0.03,0.09,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2356"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109716"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2356"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2356"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92113"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"1397"},{"type":"tags","id":"2860"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41152"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109716"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents with a two-day history of sudden onset severe pain and swelling in his left first metatarsophalangeal joint. He has been feeling fatigued recently, but puts that down to being \u0027hung over\u0027 from his birthday last Saturday night. He usually only drinks one to two cans of beer socially every fortnight but consumed around 8-10 cans over that weekend. He is normally well, other than long term renal impairment from reflux nephropathy as a child and severe psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his vital signs are within normal limits.  The joint is swollen, erythematous and tender. Aspiration of the joint revealed needle-shaped crystals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following options would be the most appropriate long term therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prednisolone","Indomethacin","Probenecid","Colchicine","Allopurinol"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllopurinol \u003C/strong\u003Eis a xanthine oxidase inhibitor which is indicated to manage hyperuricaemia associated with gout and would be the most appropriate of the listed drugs for his long term management. This patient\u2019s history of chronic kidney disease should be taken into account when choosing the dose for his allopurinol, however, it is not a contraindication for its use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe traditionally held view that starting urate-lowering therapy in the acute phase will trigger a further gout episode have been found to be false; as long as the appropriate acute treatment (eg. \u003Cstrong\u003Eindomethacin, colchicine, prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E) are given at the same time. Furthermore, starting allopurinol during an acute attack is an ideal opportunity to initiate therapy and educate the patient while they have acute symptoms. It is important to recognise when starting urate lowering therapy to continue prophylactic therapy (e.g. colchicine, NSAIDs or prednisolone) until target urate level is reached.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProbenecid\u003C/strong\u003E is a weak uricosuric agent that is often utilised with allopurinol (first line therapy) when target serum uric acid concentration cannot be achieved with allopurinol monotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Allopurinol is the preferred drug for long-term management of gout, particularly patients with renal impairment."],"references":["Robinson PC, Stamp LK. The management of gout: Much has changed. Aust Fam Physician. 2016;45(5):299-302. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/may/the-management-of-gout-much-has-changed","Hill EM, Sky K, Sit M, Collamer A, Higgs J. Does starting allopurinol prolong acute treated gout? A randomized clinical trial. J Clin Rheumatol. 2015;21(3): 120-5. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25807090/#:~:text=Conclusions%3A%20We%20initiated%20allopurinol%20at,prolong%20the%20acute%2C%20treated%20attack."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92113"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2356"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92113"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T17:39:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T17:40:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2356"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109716"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/